Complex Name: Cytochrome bc1 Complex (Complex III)

Other Organisms:
The H+/K+ ATPase complex is also present in other mammals (e.g., Mouse), but the ATP4A-ATP4B complex is most extensively studied and most prominent in Human.'[2][4]  
'
Complex Function:
This complex forms the gastric H+/K+ ATPase, a proton pump located in the apical membrane of gastric parietal cells. It is responsible for exchanging H+ ions (protons) with K+ ions across the membrane, thus driving gastric acid secretion in the human stomach.'[2][3][4][5]  
'
Proteins:
Potassium-transporting ATPase alpha chain 1 (catalytic subunit), Potassium-transporting ATPase subunit beta (regulatory subunit)'[2][4]  
'
